WRF derivative-work clarification
---------------------------------

The Weather Research and Forecasting model (WRF), and in particular its
Advanced Research WRF (ARW) dynamical core, is a community open-source model
developed and maintained primarily at the U.S. National Center for Atmospheric
Research (NCAR) / Mesoscale and Microscale Meteorology Laboratory and the
National Centers for Environmental Prediction (NCEP).

wrf_gpu is a clean-slate, independent re-implementation in Python and JAX. It
is not derived from the WRF Fortran source code. It reproduces the structure
of WRF's small-step operators (Runge-Kutta 3 outer step, acoustic substep
recurrence, Arakawa C-grid staggering, terrain-following mass coordinate) and
WRF-compatible interfaces (wrfinput / wrfbdy / wrfout NetCDF schemas at the
operator-by-operator savepoint level) sufficient to validate against WRF
Fortran reference output, but the source code is not a translation of WRF
Fortran.

The names "WRF" and "Weather Research and Forecasting Model" are referenced
descriptively for scientific accuracy and are property of their respective
owners. This project is independent of and not endorsed by NCAR, UCAR, NOAA,
or any other organisation associated with the WRF community.

If you are looking for the canonical WRF source distribution, see
<https://github.com/wrf-model/WRF>.
